# WBR 10

## 07.11.2025 Family Dinneroo WBR \- Week 10 \- *For Offline Review*

Author(s)/Contributor(s): [Abi Horner](mailto:abi.horner@deliveroo.co.uk) [Nico Phillpott](mailto:nicholas.phillpott@deliveroo.com.au)[Chloe Morgan](mailto:chloe.morgan@deliveroo.co.uk)[Johanne Soeun Chu](mailto:johanne.chu@deliveroo.com)[Iain Willmore](mailto:iain.willmore@deliveroo.co.uk)[Simon Jones](mailto:simon.jones@deliveroo.co.uk)[Chloe Hobson](mailto:chloe.hobson@deliveroo.co.uk)[James Barnes](mailto:james.barnes@deliveroo.co.uk)[Lina Gallego](mailto:lina.gallego@deliveroo.co.uk)[Leon Man](mailto:leon.man@deliveroo.co.uk)[Sheena Kotadia](mailto:sheena.kotadia@deliveroo.co.uk)[Anna Lawrence](mailto:anna.lawrence@deliveroo.co.uk)[Simon Jones](mailto:simon.jones@deliveroo.co.uk)

***Follow up actions added to [8\. Follow-ups](#bookmark=kix.p64jsmr92v50)***

### Summary (w/c 3.11.2025)

**Slower OV growth in W10 (+6% WoW), with GTV \+4% WoW to ¬£195.8k, however our platform penetration (orders in FTT zones during window) continues to increase to 2.38% (+14ppt WoW).**

[***Proposition Performance:***](#bookmark=kix.ooej1127jodj) 

* We continue to see positive signs of engagement with the proposition:  
  * Returning-to-FTT cx and OV are up WoW: they accounted for 37% of cx this week (vs 32% last week), and 39% of of OV this week (vs 34% last week), supporting product-market fit.  
  * Scheduled orders are also rising (19% vs 18% last week), suggesting some of the decline last week may have been driven by half-term behaviours.  
* However, there are some areas to monitor:  
  * Ratings have declined for the 4th consecutive week, now at 4.28.  
  * New-to-Roo and New-to-Brand metrics have also declined (1% from 2% and 34% from 37%, respectively).  
* Otherwise, the picture remains relatively steady: top performing brands, cuisines, dishes remain consistent; PLUS is stable, as is family and regional splits.  
* **Our proposition is changing behaviour for families** \- from in-app survey data, there is a significant shift (47% \- p \< 0.001) in the portion of families ordering Family Dinneroo, vs non-Dinneroo orders, showing that it is majority Families who are engaged by the proposition.

[***Marketing:***](#bookmark=kix.nguuwd1xxj9t) 

**Media Insights:** Next burst of OOH activity live as of Monday 3rd. We have investigated media upweight opportunities and our recommendation is to upweight spend behind our hero Sky talent partnership across both BVOD & paid social as this builds on the existing partnership foundation and maximises asset use in premium video environments. It also means we can continue to geo-target to FTT zones which minimises wastage. Full details of the proposal can be found [here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/10CSlNToiKJpf0HadaMEbkVtu0S6Cq_xstuP1_bZ7ZhQ/edit?usp=sharing).

Our first consumer pulse survey was released today (07/11) and we will have initial results to share by next steer co (13/11). The survey looks at unprompted awareness, prompted awareness & concept appeal.

**DXGY:** Wave 1 step completion ended 04/11. Performance continues to pace behind business case assumptions, working with CRM and Product teams to drive improvement. Wave 2 set up to launch Mon 10 November, where XP will be the same as Wave 1, removing Cx with a live DXGY journey. 

Key Drivers: 10.9k have entered in total, with 639 Cx completing all steps. To date, ¬£16.1k vouchers have been earned (+43% WoW), with spend at ¬£8.1k (vs total budget ¬£1m). 

[***Operations Performance***](#bookmark=kix.qaxr1xiqqx4y) ***and [Care:](#bookmark=kix.8phiwqoqjh8d)*** 

**B10s:** 

* All key B10s have improved WoW however continue to be elevated vs. Non-Dinneroo mealtimes. Unacceptable lates decreased \-1.03 ppt WoW to 10.35%, RWT reducing significantly to 6.4% (-3.1ppt WoW), and OI decreased \-0.34ppt WoW to 3.24%.  
* This week, Px Ops flagged seven partners with ops focus as well as 13 brands with app ratings \<4.3 within the Px Mobilisation tracker, which were then discussed in detail on the bi-weekly Operating Theatre. Focus brands saw total OI improve \-0.43ppt WoW (PizzaExpress and Banana Tree saw increases WoW) with RWT improving \-4.33ppt WoW (Prezzo saw increases WoW).   
* Warnings have been escalated to Prezzo, and Pho, who are declining in operational performance.

**Care:**

* **Claims:** increased vs prior week at 7.26% orders with a claim (+0.16 ppt WoW) and average claim amount at ¬£14.93 (+14p WoW), reflecting poorer partner operational performance, with Missing Items remaining the top offender for CCPO at 21p, while Unacceptable Lates reduced to 3.07%, reflecting slightly improved RWT and less strain on network.  
* **OTP: 54p per Dinneroo order** (-11p WoW), which is **\+44p above [target](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1VI8MI8jZlmiXNNKKB_cWaeiW9eH3rQ-LK4Gbrv_FJsw/edit)** (10p) and **\+33p above budget** (21p), reflecting lower Unacceptable Lates as above

* **Order Composition**  
  * **Ordering patterns** \- scheduled orders are up vs last week, possibly influenced by lower usage during half term  
    * 19% scheduled (vs 18% last 2 weeks)  
  * **Top performing brands, cuisines, dishes** \- top brands, cuisines and dishes remain constant  
    * Top 5 brands: Pho, Wagamama, Dishoom, PEX, Banana Tree (same as last week)  
    * Top cuisines: Asian dominates (54% vs 52% last week), followed by Indian (15% vs 15% last week) and  Italian (12% vs 12% last week)  
    * Top 3 dishes: Wags Family Chicken Katsu, Pho‚Äôs Pho the Whole Family and Dishoom‚Äôs Chicken Ruby (same as last week)  
* **Cx Composition \-** New-to-Roo and new-to-brand are down, while PLUS is stable. Returning-to-FTT continues to grow from a cx and OV share perspective. From a demographic POV, family split and location split remain similar.   
  * **New-to-Roo Cx:** 1% cx are new-to-platform (vs 2% last week)  
  * **New-to-Brand Cx:**  34% of orders are new to brand (vs 37% last week)  
  * **PLUS / Frequent Cx:** 66% of orders are from PLUS users (vs 65% last week); 61% return to platform (vs 60% last week)  
  * **Returning-to-FTT:** Returning-to-FTT cx and OV are up WoW: they accounted for 37% of cx this week (vs 32% last week), and 39% of of OV this week (vs 34% last week).

* **Family split:** 16% Families per LBDS (vs 16% last week)  
  * **Location:** Similar to previous week: FTT OV composition by region closely aligns to total Roo GTV composition by region  
* **Cx Behaviour** \- Ratings continue to decline  
  * **Ratings:** Down for the 4th week in a row: 4.28 (vs 4.41 last week); 1\* orders 8% (vs 7% last week), 69% 5\* (vs 73% last week)

### 2\. Marketing 

#### A) Media Insights ([Emily Lodge](mailto:emily.burke@deliveroo.co.uk)[Liz Wetz](mailto:liz.wetz@deliveroo.co.uk)[Russell Jackson-Pugh](mailto:russell.pugh@deliveroo.co.uk)) 

### 

* We continue to be live across all channels with our next burst of OOH activity live as of Monday 3rd.  
* We have investigated media upweight opportunities and our recommendation is to upweight spend behind our hero Sky talent partnership across both BVOD & paid social as this builds on the existing partnership foundation and maximises asset use in premium video environments. It also means we can continue to geo-target to FTT zones which minimises wastage. Full details of the proposal can be found here [here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/10CSlNToiKJpf0HadaMEbkVtu0S6Cq_xstuP1_bZ7ZhQ/edit?usp=sharing)	  
* In paid social (discover pillar) our pacing has picked up and is now on track to deliver in full. Recent optimisations have led to a significant positive update from our Brand Lift study.  First measurement (6-19 Oct) results showed a promising \+3.37% increase in Ad Recall among the users who saw our ads (the test group) compared to the control group.   
* For digital audio our listen through rate continues to exceed benchmarks suggesting the audience we are reaching resonates with the ad. However postcode targeting continues to restrict impression and spend delivery. Our recommendation at this point in the campaign is to simplify our asset mix and reduce from 2 to 1 assets in this channel. Once approved this can be action immediately in w/c 10/11.  
* We have seen more micro-influencer affiliate content come through this week on our Metapic platform (16 unique influencers, 66 orders, ¬£2k OV) however this is still below our expectations so we are continuing to expand the network of creators we are going out to  
* Our first consumer pulse survey was released today (07/11) and we will have initial results to share by next steer co (13/11). The survey looks at unprompted awareness, prompted awareness & concept appeal.  
* On 20th October in Steer Co we will provide a deepdive mid-campaign analysis alongside any proposals for further optimisations to the plan

#### B) CRM & Digital Marketing Performance Insights ([Lina Gallego](mailto:lina.gallego@deliveroo.co.uk)[Leon Man](mailto:leon.man@deliveroo.co.uk) ) 

**CRM:**   
**W/C 3 Nov:** This week we had the strongest performance of Family time since launch. We led with a Great Brands message, which drove higher CTR in email (0.4% vs 0.3% previous weeks) and push (1% vs 0.7% previous weeks). Leading with value is a proven way in CRM to drive CTR and conversion. 

**W/C 11 Nov:** We will be launching the Day of the Week XP, ‚Öì of the audience will receive FT email and push on Sunday, Tuesday, and Thursday @12:00 pm. We will be leading with Px selection messaging for all Cx. See table below for copy. 

Continuous improvement: 

* Further targeting proposal \- exclude tribe segment ‚ÄúBig Brand Loyalist‚Äù from email from w/c 17/11. We tested for two weeks sending to different tribes to understand CTR and FT conversion. Big Brand loyalist drove 0 orders at a CTR 0.1% for email. Segment size \~153K Cx.    
* We are working on wagamamas solus email to launch on w/c 17/11. This email would reach \~1M of our FT audience. We expect to share creatives early next week prior to scheduling email and push.  
* We are creating a new inspiration email using our OOH imagery to launch on w/c 17.11. This email would reach \~800K of our FT audience. We expect to share creatives early next week prior to scheduling email and push.  
* Following up on feedback from last week, for the PX email launching on 24.11, we want to identify zones with more PX in the area, and communicate ‚ÄúNew in Family Dinneroo‚Äù messaging.

This week, Px Ops flagged seven partners with ops focus as well as 13 brands with app ratings \<4.3 within the Px Mobilisation tracker, which were then discussed in detail on the bi-weekly Operating Theatre. Focus brands saw total OI improve \-0.43ppt WoW (PizzaExpress and Banana Tree saw increases WoW) with RWT improving \-4.33ppt WoW (Prezzo saw increases WoW).

For more detailed information, using care claim comments and customer comments, we can see:

* Wagamama (24 Issues): Frequent spillages and leaks, underfilled family bundles, and poor food quality (undercooked or cold).  
* Pho (21 Issues): Major spillages of soups and sauces, incorrect or inconsistent items, and poor food quality (cold or undercooked).  
* PizzaExpress (18 Issues): Wrong or missing items, burnt or cold food, and packaging damage during delivery.  
* Giggling Squid (14 Issues): Widespread spillages from curry packaging, poor packaging integrity, and overcooked or bland dishes.  
* Dishoom (10 Issues): Spilled curries, incorrect or missing items (e.g., dal substitutions), and occasional contamination concerns.  
* Banana Tree (8 Issues): Undercooked rice, poor quality or stale food, incorrect items, and misleading portion sizes.  
* Kricket (6 Issues): Spilled or crushed curries, incorrect dishes, and undercooked sides.  
* Bill‚Äôs (5 Issues): Crushed or damaged packaging and cold, poorly cooked meals.  
* Cocotte (5 Issues): Leaking packaging, incorrect items in bundles, and inconsistent flavors.  
* Las Iguanas (5 Issues): Missing items, crushed packaging, and poor service follow-up.  
* Farmer J (4 Issues): Crushed or spilled packaging and missing components like sides.  
* Others (1‚Äì2 Issues Each): Itsu, Bella Italia, Prezzo, Saravana Bhavan, Chaska, and Zambrero ‚Äî isolated cases of missing items, spillages, and poor food quality.

#### B) On-Time Promise 

This week‚Äôs gross OTP performance is **54p per Dinneroo order** (-11p WoW), which is **\+44p above [target](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1VI8MI8jZlmiXNNKKB_cWaeiW9eH3rQ-LK4Gbrv_FJsw/edit)** (10p) and **\+33p above budget** (21p). We observe WoW declines every day except for Monday (+28p) with performance stabilising as Unacceptable Lates reduce WoW (0.72ppt) and the delta between non-FTT order Lates and FTT orders reduces from 1.16ppt delta to 0.39ppt, reflecting better operations during our window.
